Lesson: Logic Reuse with Wrappers
One of the most powerful use cases for property wrappers is enforcing rules on your data, such as clamping a number to a range, trimming a string, or validating an email address. By moving this logic into a wrapper, you make your main data structures more readable and less prone to errors.

Core Concepts:
1. Encapsulated Logic: The 'how' of the validation is hidden inside the wrapper struct.
2. Declarative Usage: You simply mark a property with '@Clamped' to opt into the behavior.
3. Automatic Initialization: Swift calls the wrapper's initializer when the struct containing the property is created.

Example:
    @propertyWrapper
    struct Normalized {
        private var value: Double = 0
        var wrappedValue: Double {
            get { value }
            set { value = max(0, min(1, newValue)) }
        }
    }

Note: This pattern reduces boilerplate and ensures consistent data validation across your entire app.

solution:
@propertyWrapper
struct Clamped {
    private var value: Int
    init(wrappedValue: Int) {
        value = min(max(0, wrappedValue), 100)
    }
    var wrappedValue: Int {
        get { value }
        set { value = min(max(0, newValue), 100) }
    }
}

struct Gauge {
    @Clamped var pressure: Int
}

var gauge = Gauge(pressure: 120)
print(gauge.pressure)

