lesson:
Lesson: Error Associated Values
Simply knowing that an error occurred is often not enough. Swift allows you to attach relevant data to your custom error cases using associated values. This data can then be extracted and used by the caller to recover from the error or provide more helpful diagnostics.

Core Concepts:
1. Contextual Errors: Define an error case with a payload, like 'case validationFailed(reason: String)'.
2. Throwing with Data: When you throw the error, you pass in the specific data: 'throw MyError.tooLow(900)'.
3. Pattern Matching: Use 'catch' with pattern matching to extract the associated value for use in your error handling logic.

Example:
    enum FileError: Error { case notFound(String) }
    do {
        try openFile("config.txt")
    } catch FileError.notFound(let name) {
        print("The file \(name) was missing")
    }

Note: This makes your error handling system much more robust and informative than using simple, data-less error cases.

solution:
enum HeatError: Error {
    case tooLow(Int)
}

func checkHeat(_ value: Int) throws {
    if value < 1000 {
        throw HeatError.tooLow(value)
    }
}

do {
    try checkHeat(900)
} catch HeatError.tooLow(let value) {
    print("Too low: \(value)")
}

