Swift was designed to coexist with Objective-C, allowing developers to use legacy codebases and Apple's extensive framework library. One of the ways this is achieved is through 'bridging'—automatic conversion between certain Swift types and their Objective-C equivalents.

Core Concepts:
1. @objc: Use this attribute to expose Swift classes, methods, and properties to the Objective-C runtime.
2. Toll-Free Bridging: Some types can be used interchangeably between the two languages without any performance cost (e.g., 'String' and 'NSString').
3. Dynamic Dispatch: Objective-C relies on dynamic dispatch (finding methods at runtime), which is different from Swift's default static or vtable dispatch.

Example:
    @objc class MyController: NSObject {
        @objc func handleAction() { ... }
    }

Note: Understanding bridging is essential for integrating Swift into established iOS and macOS projects.

